About this hotel

This chic riad is 2 km from open-air food stalls at Jemaa el-Fnaa, 3 km from the 12th-century Koutoubia Mosque and a 15-minute walk from Bahia Palace.

Check-in time: 2:00 PM

    Tyler Wood4 years ago on Google
    1/5
    Really wanted to like this hotel. The hotel itself is beautiful but they just got so many things wrong. …
    Really wanted to like this hotel. The hotel itself is beautiful but they just got so many things wrong.
    Pros:
    -Beautiful lobby, multiple floors with great nooks to chill. Our room was small but ok.
    Cons:
    - Disorganized. We booked a room with two beds but when we arrived they gave us a room with one single bed. They did not tell us this until after the elaborate hour-long check in process at which point it was already very late and we could not find another option for the night. The staff was not helpful at all in helping find an alternative.
    - Bad service. The hotel did not try very hard to fix our room situation. The staff did not speak good english which is rare in Morocco. I asked them if there was laundry service and they understood what I meant but had no idea this was a thing a hotel might offer.
    - Terrible wifi. The signal is weak all throughout the building and even when you are connected the speed is so slow you can’t even load a webpage. We had better internet service at our hotels in the dessert than here. The internet was unusable.
    - Little things in the room: there were no accessible outlets for charging devices in our room, so i had to plug my things in in the bathroom which was weird. The shower had no curtain, the pressure was very weak the and mount for the shower wand was broken.
    - Location. Far from everything, not convenient.
    All in all I have to say this was a really bad experience. We left after one night and found a new hotel which was so much nicer.

    Josh M Paul3 years ago on Google
    4/5
    After the flight, we boarded our ride to the hotel. It was hot. Seriously hot. And the car hadn’t any air conditioning, so you can imagine hoping for an oasis. The journey made the experience ever more enchanting. Marrakesh is stunning. …
    After the flight, we boarded our ride to the hotel. It was hot. Seriously hot. And the car hadn’t any air conditioning, so you can imagine hoping for an oasis. The journey made the experience ever more enchanting. Marrakesh is stunning. Raw. Unforgivable. Poor and rich. Historic. And majestic. The old part, within the walls. We entered the tightest tunnel to enter. Traffic was manic, no order or safety, just ride and drive is the Moto.
    Twenty minutes of eye opening scenes, and culture, we arrived at Road le Parroquet Bleu. The street looked almost biblical. Dry, but rich in colour, cool in the shade. It’s the total opposite to a London Street for example.
    The wooden gate to the riad, was very large, and carved so intricate. We were welcomed in and the first thought, oasis. The Court Yard and hall ways were beautiful. Mosaic tiles, the sound of trickling water from the fountain, the fresh smell of flowers and mint tea. Rest rooms adorn with fine art and ornaments, and the most comfortable seating. I sat in every one.
    Checking in was simple and the host was attentive polite and seriously welcoming. “This is your home whilst you stay. So, explore and embrace it as your home”. And we did.
    Once taken to the room, mouths open, we explored the riad, every inch of it, and it was the most peculiar feeling. Outside was nauseous and dusty, loud and busy, and within these walls, was a peaceful ambiance throughout. White, blue, wooden, stone courtyards and balconies. A pool surrounded with plants like orange and lime trees.
    The upper terrace for sunbathing eating drinking.
    The room was spacious, came with a steam and sauna (I was so happy) comfortable big big big bed, and our own courtyard, for private use. Only one issue was the very noisy air conditioning machine.
    Call to prayer is quite an experience, but, it comes with the culture and to experience everything and return to this riad, made it all worth while.
    Again. The staff are exceptional. Cleanliness and hygiene highly considered. Great food both morning and evening.
    Any riad, is an oasis. I’d recommend.

    Medina

    Hammam bath houses and covered spice and textile souks line the maze of cobblestoned lanes in the Medina, which occupies Marrakesh’s original fortified citadel. At night, Jemaa el-Fna square teems with snake charmers, folk dancers, and street food vendors serving all manner of food. Bahia Palace and Le Jardin Secret are 19th-century complexes open to the public, with ornate courtyards, mosaics, and gardens.

    About this hotel

    This chic riad is 2 km from open-air food stalls at Jemaa el-Fnaa, 3 km from the 12th-century Koutoubia Mosque and a 15-minute walk from Bahia Palace. …

    Airy, individually decorated rooms offer flat-screen TVs and Wi-Fi access, as well as safes, minibars and en suite bathrooms. Some have 4-poster beds, living areas, fireplaces and/or terraces.

    Breakfast is included. Other amenities consist of a polished restaurant, a hammam, a lounge, and meeting and event space. There's also an inner courtyard with a fountain, an outdoor pool and seating. Babysitting and massage services are available, as is an airport shuttle (fee).
